point : especially in case of nationalist conflict or terrorist attack , it may be extremely difficult to have a non biased jury . in northern island , for example , juror may sympathize with violent offender and acquit them despite a preponderance of evidence . similarly , it can be a struggle to appoint non bias jury for terrorism trial post 9 11 . in 2003 , the lackwana six be accuse of aid a foreign terrorist organization . the magistrate note that understandably , the infamous , dastardly and tragic deed and event of september 11 , 2001 have cause a maelstrom of human emotion to . . . create a human reservoir of strong emotional feeling such a fear , anxiety and hatred as well a a feeling of paranoia . . . these be strong emotion of a negative nature which , if not appropriately check , cause the ability of one to properly reason to . . . be blind . questions about jury impartiality have be raise in multiple similar case , even lead some defendant to claim that they plead guilty out of resignation that the jury would inevitably be bias and refuse to acquit . 1 the implication be that in some trial , jury may be unable to make impartial decision , thus make the trial unfair . the only way for justice to be do , in such case , be to allow a judge to decide the verdict . 
counterpoint : first , there be check in place to help prevent biased decision and second , the less objective nature of jury be not necessarily bad . first , in most jury system , a judge can overturn a guilty verdict if s he believe that the jury make a faulty decision1 . judges can also order retrial in case of guilty verdict , if they believe there be procedural error . furthermore , in most country there be a phase of the jury selection process in which both the prosecution and defence can object to a juror ; in many country each side get a specific number of these unconditional 'peremptory challenge . ' that allow blatantly bias juror to be exclude . perhaps most importantly , at least with jury there be multiple people make the decision , a oppose to a sole judge : there be no reason to assume that a lone judge will be less biased , just because of his 'professional training . 'but second , have a subjective body make the decision be not necessarily bad . we obviously don't want people to be sway by unchecked prejudice , but one of the point of have a jury be that it allow all part of the community to participate in the judicial process and provide input that disconnect and often homogenous government official cannot . for example , the diplock court establish in 1970s northern ireland eliminate jury , and along with them , jury bias . this result in high conviction rate for violent offender , but also have the negative effect of exclude the catholic minority from the administration of justice and judge bias remain , a evidence by the failure of the court to eliminate the gap between catholic and protestant conviction rate . 2 
